with lower-dimensional data, but preserve as much of the data\u2019s variance .", "Two things to know about this are:", "Note: The following list is taken from Wikipedia (Source: Wikipedia)", "But what are the Principle Components? Great question! The principle components are Eigenvectors of the data\u2019s covariance matrix. So we do not have to go so much into the Math elements, watch the next two videos to better understand Eigenvectors, Eigenvalues, and Covariance matrix.", "Eigenvector \u2192 (Of a Linear Transformation) is a nonzero vector that changes by a scalar factor when a linear transform is applied to it.", "Eigenvalues \u2192 The factor by which the Eigenvector is scaled", "Covariance Matrix \u2192 A covariance matrix is a square matrix giving the covariance between each pair of elements of a given random vector. Any covariance matrix is symmetric and positive semi-definite and its main diagonal contains variances (i.e., the covariance of each element with itself) (Source: Wikipedia).", "To perform PCA, we ought to get the Eigenvectors and Eigenvalues from the covariance matrix of our data. In order to do this, we mean normalize our data then get the covariance matrix, and finally perform a singular value decomposition (SVD).", "Next, we must project our data to a new set of features using the eigenvectors and eigenvalues we retrieved from the last step from the previous task. To do this, we take the dot product of our features and the first n columns of our Eigenvectors. If we want to reduce the dimensionality of our data to 2 dimensions, we\u2019d use the first two columns of the Eigenvectors.", "We are now ready to implement PCA and we will use it to visualize the Iris Dataset.", "Let\u2019s start by using the sklearn framework to perform PCA on the iris dataset\u2026", "For our own implementation, we begin by getting the uncorrelated features and to do that we follow the steps in Figure 2.", "Mean Normalize Data \u2192 Get Covariance Matrix \u2192 